  "text": "Yet another approach is to use the classic sign test, which is aimed at making inferences about P(X < Y). As is evident, this probability provides a useful perspective on the nature of the difference between the two dependent variables under study beyond simply comparing measures of central tendency. The R function signt performs the sign test, which by default uses the method derived by [CITATION_1] . If the goal is to ensure that the confidence interval has probability coverage at least 1 − α, rather than approximately equal to 1 − α, the Schilling and Doi (2014) method can be used by setting the argument SD = TRUE when using the R function signt. In contrast to the Schilling and Doi method, p-values can be computed when using the Agresti and Coull technique. Another negative feature of the Schilling and Doi method is that execution time can be extremely high even with a moderately large sample size.",
